
[1]hectical

   HEC'TICAL, a. [Gr. habit of body, to have.] Habitual; denoting a slow,
   continual fever, marked by preternatural, though remitting heat, which
   precedes and accompanies the consumption or phthisis; as a hectic
   fever.

   1. Affected with hectic fevers; as a hectic patient.

   2. Troubled with a morbid heat.

   No hectic student scares the gentle maid.
